<subSubSection pageNumber="789" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="789">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="789">Note:</emphasis>
Smith &amp; Downs designated a Plumier specimen (P) as the type. It would not, however, have been studied by Linnaeus and is not original material for the name. Although one illustration, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Catesby’s">Catesby's</normalizedToken>
2: t. 89, is mentioned in the protologue, it is accompanied by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“?”">&quot;?&quot;</normalizedToken>
, indicating 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
doubts as to whether it belonged with this name. These seem to have been well-founded as the plate is identifiable as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schultes) Roemer &amp; Schultes" authorityName="Roemer &amp; Schultes" baseAuthorityName="Schultes" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Tillandsia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="balbisiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="789">Tillandsia balbisiana</emphasis>
(Schultes) Roemer &amp; Schultes
</taxonomicName>
(see Howard &amp; Staples in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="789">J. Arnold Arbor.</emphasis>
64: 514. 1983). In the absence of original material, Smith &amp; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Downs’">Downs'</normalizedToken>
choice is treated as a neotypification under Art. 9.8.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
